<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-076-269 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 225 297</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 29 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Silicon Valley Group restructures.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stokell, Ian.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Silicon Valley Group Inc. (Management).andO;Topic:     Sales OrganizationsReorganizationCustomer RelationsComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SILICON VALLEY GROUP RESTRUCTURES 08/29/91 SAN JOSE, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1991AUG 29 (NB) -- In an effort it claims will concentrate resources and betterserve customers, Silicon Valley Group has consolidated its sales and serviceoperations into a single corporate entity.andM;Carol Durrant, spokesperson for SVG, told Newsbytes that the company was&quot;finding that account management works better under a unifiedstructure.....where a customer could call their sales representative and talkabout any of our products.&quot;andM;The company's Track Systems, Thermco Systems and SVG Lithography Systems hadpreviously operated sales and service functions independently.andM;Apart from pooling resources, Durrant also said that the company intends toexpand its cross training and cross utilization programs to meet customerrequirements.andM;Charles R. Joseph will head the new organization, and has been promoted tocorporate vice president of worldwide field operations.andP;  He will also guideall corporate communication activities.andM;According to the company, the field operations organization will also serveas a link between the customer and SVG's three business units, conveying newprocess and product mandates to ensure that development efforts are in syncwith the customers emerging requirements.andM;(Ian Stokell/19910829/Press Contact: Carol Durrant, Silicon Valley GroupInc., 408-432-9300)</TEXT></DOC>